definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To measure the duration of.
( transitive ) To measure the speed of.
examples: He was clocked at 155 miles per hour.
When the boxer let down his guard, his opponent clocked him.

definitions.definition: ( transitive , informal ) To notice ; to take notice of (someone or something).
examples: Clock the wheels on that car!

definitions.definition: ( transitive , informal , with as ) To recognize ; to assess , register .
examples: I'd already clocked her as someone who couldn't reliably be believed when she spoke. And now this too!

definitions.definition: ( transitive , informal ) To identify (someone) as having some attribute ( for example, being trans or gay ) .
examples: Once my transition was complete I considered moving to London, where I felt there was less chance of being clocked and a larger support network.

definitions.definition: ( British , slang ) To falsify the reading of the odometer of a vehicle .
examples: I don't believe that car has done only 40,000 miles. It's been clocked.

definitions.definition: ( transitive , British , New Zealand , Australia , slang ) To beat a video game .
examples: Have you clocked that game yet?
